Thoughts on Overriding Default Controls

When you override default browser controls, you’re relying on the user being able to discover the interaction for themselves.

For our date picker using roving tabindex, Arrow keys are a pretty standard function. It shouldn’t be an impossible learning curve for someone to figure out how to move around the days and weeks.

However, think about something less intuitive like implementing keyboard shortcuts in your application.

How are you going to help the user understand what the shortcuts are? How will they know they’re even available?

You could add instructions for screen reader users or you could add a little help button to launch help documentation, perhaps. But your component controls and interactions should be as discoverable as possible without putting a cognitive burden on users.

As designers and developers, there are times when we think we’re making things more intuitive but they end up being more confusing.

My advice will always be to test your complex interactions with people who rely on the keyboard and Assistive Technologies.

Wrapping Up Focus Management

Implementing the roving tabindex pattern is a bit involved. But it’s a nice technique to have in your pocket.

While there are other ways to implement it, the underlying principles are the same:

Keep one element in a group focusable at a time by changing the tabindex attribute value from 0 to -1 depending on where the user is trying to get to. You will likely need to handle focus as tabindex values are updated to keep the user’s focus point in the right spot.

There was a lot going on in the date picker component, so feel free to reference the code if you need to implement a similar pattern in your own projects.
